gdom":"Wantage, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Church of Saint Peter and Saint Paul, Church Street, Wantage, Vale of White Horse district, Berkshire, England,, United":"Wantage, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Rampayn was born in 1292, in Wantage, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John Childrey De Rampayn, was 27 and her mother, Juliana De Chelrye, was 25. She married Henry Childrey in 1315, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1324, in her hometown, at the age of 32, and was buried in Wantage, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1292–1324":"1292–1324","1294–Female":"1294–Surnud","1270–1336":"1270–1336","1320–1374":"1320–1374","1325–1372":"1325–1372","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1268–1326":"1268–1326","Abt 1315":"1315","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1326":"1326","1325":"1325","1336":"1336","1324":"1324","1268":"1268","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","Wantage, Vale of the White Horse district, Oxfordshire